      practice: [
        { q: 'Solve 2x − 7 = 11 for x.', a: '9', difficulty: 'easy', hint: 'Add 7, then divide by 2.', solution: '2x = 18, so x = 9.' },
        { q: 'Factor x² − 9.', a: '(x-3)(x+3)', acceptable: ['(x+3)(x-3)'], difficulty: 'easy', hint: 'Difference of squares.', solution: 'x² − 9 = (x − 3)(x + 3).' },
        { q: 'Solve x² − 7x + 12 = 0.', a: 'x=3 or x=4', acceptable: ['3,4', '4,3', 'x=4 or x=3', '3 and 4'], difficulty: 'medium', hint: 'Two numbers that multiply to 12 and add to 7.', solution: 'Factor as (x − 3)(x − 4) = 0, so x = 3 or x = 4.' },
      ],
      subtopics: [
        {
          id: 'algebra-linear',
          name: 'Linear equations',
          level: 'Beginner',
          readTime: '5 min',
          summary: 'One unknown, one equation, one answer. Every other kind of equation is a harder version of this.',
          body: [
            { type: 'p', text: 'A linear equation in one variable looks like ax + b = c for some known numbers a, b, c, and one unknown x. The solution is always x = (c − b)/a, as long as a ≠ 0. That formula is obvious once you stare at it, but the point of the subject is the procedure: add the same thing to both sides, multiply both sides by the same thing, never divide by zero.' },
            { type: 'p', text: 'Two linear equations in two unknowns form a system. Three main techniques solve them: substitution (solve one for one unknown, plug in), elimination (add or subtract the equations so one unknown drops out), or matrices (linear algebra). In a first algebra course, substitution is usually taught first.' },
          ],
          keyTerms: ['linear equation', 'solution', 'system of equations', 'substitution', 'elimination'],
          examples: [
            {
              title: 'Elimination',
              problem: 'Solve the system: 2x + y = 7; x − y = 2.',
              steps: [
                { text: 'Add the equations to eliminate y.', math: '(2x + y) + (x − y) = 7 + 2 = 9' },
                { text: 'Simplify.', math: '3x = 9, so x = 3' },
                { text: 'Plug x = 3 back into either equation to find y.', math: 'y = 2x − 7 = 6 − 7 = −1 — wait, use 2x + y = 7: y = 7 − 6 = 1' },
              ],
              answer: 'x = 3, y = 1',
            },
          ],
          practice: [
            { q: 'Solve 5x + 3 = 2x − 9.', a: '-4', acceptable: ['−4', 'x=-4'], difficulty: 'easy', hint: 'Move x-terms to one side.', solution: '5x − 2x = −9 − 3; 3x = −12; x = −4.' },
            { q: 'Solve the system x + y = 10; x − y = 4.', a: 'x=7, y=3', acceptable: ['7,3', 'x=7,y=3', '(7,3)'], difficulty: 'medium', hint: 'Add the two equations.', solution: 'Sum: 2x = 14 → x = 7. Then y = 10 − 7 = 3.' },
          ],
        },
        {
          id: 'algebra-quadratic',
          name: 'Quadratic equations',
          level: 'Beginner',
          readTime: '6 min',
          summary: 'ax² + bx + c = 0. Three tools: factoring, completing the square, the quadratic formula.',
          body: [
            { type: 'p', text: 'A quadratic equation has the form ax² + bx + c = 0. If the left side factors nicely — if you can write it as (x − p)(x − q) — the solutions are x = p and x = q. If it does not, the quadratic formula handles every case: x = (−b ± √(b² − 4ac))/(2a). The thing under the square root, b² − 4ac, is called the discriminant; if it is negative, the solutions are complex.' },
            { type: 'p', text: 'Completing the square is the method that proves the quadratic formula, and it is worth knowing for its own sake. It shows you that the vertex of the parabola y = ax² + bx + c sits at x = −b/(2a) — which matters for optimization problems in the next course up.' },
          ],
          keyTerms: ['quadratic formula', 'discriminant', 'factoring', 'completing the square', 'parabola'],
          examples: [
            {
              title: 'Factoring when it works',
              problem: 'Solve x² + 5x + 6 = 0.',
              steps: [
                { text: 'Find two numbers that multiply to 6 and add to 5.' },
                { text: 'Those numbers are 2 and 3, so factor.', math: '(x + 2)(x + 3) = 0' },
                { text: 'A product is zero only if one factor is zero.', math: 'x = −2 or x = −3' },
              ],
              answer: 'x = −2 or x = −3',
            },
          ],
          practice: [
            { q: 'Solve x² = 16.', a: 'x=4 or x=-4', acceptable: ['±4', '4,-4', '-4,4'], difficulty: 'easy', hint: 'Two square roots, positive and negative.', solution: 'x = ±4.' },
            { q: 'Use the quadratic formula to solve x² + 2x − 3 = 0.', a: 'x=1 or x=-3', acceptable: ['1,-3', '-3,1'], difficulty: 'medium', hint: 'a=1, b=2, c=−3. Discriminant = 4 + 12 = 16.', solution: 'x = (−2 ± 4)/2. So x = 1 or x = −3.' },
          ],
        },
        {
          id: 'algebra-functions',
          name: 'Functions and their graphs',
          level: 'Beginner',
          readTime: '5 min',
          summary: 'The jump from equations to functions: a machine with an input and an output.',
          body: [
            { type: 'p', text: 'A function is a rule that takes an input and returns exactly one output. The notation f(x) = x² + 1 means "the function f, which sends x to x² + 1." Every x you can plug in is in the domain; every y that can come out is in the range.' },
            { type: 'p', text: 'The graph of a function is the set of points (x, f(x)) drawn in a plane. Linear functions graph as straight lines. Quadratic functions graph as parabolas. The shape of the graph is a language for the behavior of the function — and reading it fluently is the central skill of the next course, precalculus.' },
          ],
          keyTerms: ['function', 'domain', 'range', 'graph', 'slope', 'intercept'],
          practice: [
            { q: 'If f(x) = 2x + 3, what is f(5)?', a: '13', difficulty: 'easy', hint: 'Plug in 5.', solution: 'f(5) = 2·5 + 3 = 13.' },
            { q: 'What is the slope of the line y = 3x − 7?', a: '3', difficulty: 'easy', hint: 'Coefficient of x.', solution: 'In y = mx + b form, the slope m is 3.' },
            { q: 'If f(x) = x² − 4, what is f(−3)?', a: '5', difficulty: 'medium', hint: '(−3)² = 9.', solution: 'f(−3) = (−3)² − 4 = 9 − 4 = 5.' },
          ],
        },
      ],

